english:
  title: Divine Creatures Present Auspicious Omens at the Banquet for the Royal Carriage at the Residence of the Marquis of Jingang
  author: Lee Gyeou-bo
  language: eng
  text: |-
    The divine turtle bears the heavenly map, as the River Lord Fengyi bows before the royal majesty.

    I have heard that Your Imperial Majesty has graced the grand mansion of the Marquis of Jingang, where the sovereign and ministers feast together in celebration of great peace. Unable to contain my admiration and wonder, I humbly dispatch the messenger of the Clear River, bearing the precious map of heaven to receive Your Majesty's blessings for ten thousand years of life.

    The warm breeze lingers, the sun moves slowly—auspicious signs are divined in the green spring. The magnificent halls of that exquisite estate spread open their ordered banquets beneath the bright day. Though I dwell hidden in the depths, how could I neglect my joy and reverence?

    I respectfully contemplate: Your Imperial Majesty possesses knowledge as profound as the divine, your wisdom is sage and perfect. Draped in elegant robes, you transform all beneath heaven; seated in contentment, you enjoy the blessings of peace. By bestowing domains upon your faithful subjects, you have honored propriety and virtue. From the imperial palace you extend your ceremonial guard, granting the Marquis's residence the honor of your gracious presence.

    I humbly regard the esteemed lord of this house: he receives the refined essence of Mount Song, the pure virtue of the Pleiades star. His renown surpasses that of Yi Yin and the Duke of Zhou; his achievements, resplendent as clouds, rival those of generations past. His deeds exceed even those of the great Huan and Wen; thus his loyalty to the throne grows ever deeper. He has opened this vast estate that soars like clouds to receive the imperial procession. Silken robes mingle in fragrant clouds; pipes and songs rise in eager celebration.

    I reflect upon myself: the River Lord Fengyi dwells in the nine rivers' domain, presiding as sovereign of the four great waters. When the Tang dynasty arose, I offered the white map of heaven. When the great consort flourished, I presented the grand patterns of prosperity. Now that sovereign and minister share one virtue, heaven and earth send down auspicious signs. How could I, possessing the vastness of my own realm, begrudge offering precious tributes? Therefore I send forth a six-eyed celestial messenger bearing the mystical symbols of the eight trigrams, and hereby present these humble verses:

    The sage ruler brings renewal—
    his grace descends on all creatures.
    The divine turtle emerges from the river,
    the secret map upon its shell.
    The blessing of ten thousand years of life—
    this, dear turtle, is yours to give.
    Do not hoard it for yourself,
    but share it with our sovereign and his court,
    that they may enjoy longevity without measure.

    ---

    The Dragon Horse bears a scroll—the waters of Luo yield forth their divine spirit.

    I have heard that Your Imperial Majesty has honored the residence of the Marquis of Jingang, where you feast in joy and celebration. Unable to contain my happiness and praise, I humbly send forth the Dragon Horse bearing a scroll to offer my congratulations.

    The flying dragon ascends to heaven—thus great men appear. The mystical horse emerges from the waters—thereby heaven's bright mandate shines forth. I respectfully regard Your Imperial Majesty: you unite the hearts of all four quarters, embodying the virtues of the five ancient emperors. Encountering this peaceful season of the realm, noting the clear and harmonious weather, you have descended from the celestial palace to rest the phoenix canopy within the crimson mansion. You permit celestial music and open elaborate feasts within painted halls. In joy and contentment, your every recreation becomes the model for all.

    I humbly regard the esteemed lord: he has set right all under heaven, twice rebuilt the royal house. His cloud-piercing estate rises high, its crimson pillars soaring above golden halls. Gongs and drums welcome the imperial carriage into the palace of precious pearls. For one moment of grace, he presents a hundred arts of celestial dancers. Gods and men breathe in the harmonious qi, immersed in the waves of imperial kindness. The appearance of golden fish hardly suffices as an auspicious omen; the offering of black jade cannot match this blessing. Yet still I send forth the swift qilin who races beside the sun, joining the dance of beasts and birds in the courtyard. Thus I present this humble song in praise of your sage virtue:

    Humanity and sageness respond to heaven—
    green clouds float over Luo's waters.
    The mystical horse emerges from the waters—
    swift as wind, bright as lightning.
    Bearing wondrous words in its mouth—
    the yellow map and green records.
    How shall we present them?
    May the imperial age know no bounds,
    may the marquis's years stretch to a hundred million.
  footnotes:
    - The divine turtle bearing the heavenly map (河圖) is a traditional symbol of auspicious portent in Chinese mythology, associated with celestial wisdom and imperial legitimacy.
    - Fengyi (馮夷) is the Lord of the Yellow River, a river deity in Chinese tradition.
    - Yi Yin and the Duke of Zhou were legendary wise ministers of ancient China, representing ideal loyalty and governance.
    - The eight trigrams (八卦) are fundamental symbols of Daoist cosmology and divination.
    - The Dragon Horse and the scroll it bears reference the legendary beast that emerged from the Yellow River carrying the symbols that revealed the order of heaven to ancient sages.
